flowRoot.flowPara: NETs allow carbon budgets to expand, inadvertently dis-incentivising costly near-term mitigation. In a set of equivalent scenarios for meeting 2 C, the moral hazard mitigation gap between no-CCS runs versus full-tech runs is as high as 5-10 GtCO in 2030. Ethicists have expressed concern that this commits future generations to even steeper emissions reductions and locks-in a risky dependence on NETs.

Sequestering CO2 emissions on scale requires that humans assume control of major biogeochemical processes. NETs deployment levels estimated in IAMs are approximately equivalent to the entire natural land CO2 sink in 2050, and almost double it in 2100. Although sink and source trends since the 1950s clearly show an emerging "anthropocene", the intentional management of these processes strikes some ethicists as hubristic.
